<head>
<title>Duplantier: MEDIA VIOLENCE -- 5/17/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
May 17, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Media Violence</h2>


<i><blockquote>


A new report from Focus on the Family charges that the content of our  
popular media is becoming increasingly violent.
 </blockquote></i>

<P>

"Three decades ago, not one popular song encouraged robbery, rape,  
murder, assaults, or using weapons to settle disputes," says Focus on the  
Family research manager Robert Waliszewski. "In today's popular music,  
all these themes can be found -- and worse! Nothing is taboo.  
Unfortunately, America's streets and neighborhoods increasingly reflect  
this fact. What's more, since violent lyrics are a relatively new  
phenomenon, no one knows the results of raising a generation on this  
type of musical diet. In addition, teenagers have greater access to (and  
are listening to) far more music than they have in past generations." By  
the end of high school, the average teenager has listened to more than  
10,000 hours of rock music. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Waliszewski argues that "television's preoccupation with sex, violence,  
and sexualized violence would have been unthinkable in the minds of its  
early pioneers." But ugliness and depravity are pervasive on television  
today, and "TV talk shows are just the tip of the iceberg." Waliszewski  
warns that "television transmits values that are opposite to those being  
taught at home," forcing children "to choose which message to believe."  
Alarming increases in juvenile delinquency rates would seem to suggest  
that television is winning the values battle. "TV receives the lion's share  
of a young person's attention -- and does so in their most impressionable  
years," says Waliszewski. "By the time the average American child  
graduates high school, he or she will have spent nearly 20,000 hours in  
front of a television" -- twice the amount of time spent in school. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Much of the trash on television is recycled garbage from Hollywood.  
Waliszewski notes that films like "Natural Born Killers" and "Menace II  
Society" have encouraged impressionable viewers to imitate the  
unspeakable violence they glorified. But the ill effects don't end there.  
"For many undetermined others, their values were molded -- causing a  
desensitization toward violence and a loss of respect for society's laws  
and lawkeepers." 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Jerry Melchisedeck of Focus on the Family cites research identifying "a  
short-term relationship between playing violent video games and  
increased aggressive behavior in younger children." The data suggest  
that "the ill effects of video games are worse than those of TV because  
children actively control the violence rather than passively view it. In  
other words, the more children practice violent acts, the more likely they  
are to perform violent acts." 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The ability to "download" video games is one of the major appeals of the  
so-called Information Superhighway. Thirty million people worldwide  
are now hooked up to the Internet, and video games aren't the only  
noneducational diversion available to them. Pornographers and  
pedophiles are already exploiting the perverse possibilities of electronic  
mail. Waliszewski and Melchisedeck of Focus on the Family warn that  
"parents must not look to the government to protect their children. They  
must take an active role in monitoring" the content of the various  
popular media available in their own homes. 
<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




