<head>
<title>Duplantier:  Libertine Libraries  -- 3/19/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

March 19, 1996 
<br></i>

<h2>Libertine Libraries</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
Your children cannot legally buy obscene rap music albums at a record    
store. They may, however, be able to check out the same revolting trash    
at your local library. 
</i></blockquote>
<P>     
  
Imagine your 12-year-old child coming home from the public library    
with a CD or cassette tape of 2 Live Crew's vulgar rap album As Nasty    
As They Wanna Be. Do you think it's impossible? Do you think no    
publicly-funded library would purchase music glorifying the rape and    
mutilation of women? Do you think no responsible librarian would    
release such material to children? Think again.   
<p>   
Public libraries all over America have multiple copies of As Nasty As    
They Wanna Be and other violent and salacious recordings. They    
routinely loan these materials to children without the knowledge or    
permission of their parents. It's their policy to do that.   
<p>   
In the February issue of the Education Reporter, longtime teacher Helen    
Chaffee Biehle describes how she recently discovered that the public    
libraries she's loved all her life are no longer child-friendly forums for    
fact-finding and fantasizing. Having read in her local newspaper that a    
12-year-old boy had indeed been allowed to check out 2 Live Crew's    
filthy tape from one of the county libraries, Mrs. Biehle decided to call    
the library director herself and find out how this terrible mistake had    
occurred. She discovered that it was no mistake.   
<p>   
The library director was "completely calm and utterly unapologetic,"    
Mrs. Biehle recalls. Following the guidelines of the American Library    
Association's Intellectual Freedom Manual as regards the handling of    
complaints, the director offered three lines of defense. The first was an    
appeal to diversity. "Neither you nor I might approve of As Nasty As    
They Wanna Be," she conceded, "but we serve a diverse population."    
Then there was the philosophical dodge. "Not to buy the tape would be    
making a moral judgment," she said. "We can't do that." The ultimate    
defense, however, was an American Library Association document called    
the Library Bill of Rights, which has absolutely no legal standing but    
purports to prohibit "censorship" on the basis of age.   
 <p>  
The great irony, of course, is that the guardians of intellectual freedom at    
the American Library Association are anything but tolerant when it    
comes to considering the opinions of others. It's not diversity that they    
believe in, but perversity. They make moral judgments -- or should we    
say, immoral judgments -- all the time. Censorship is the very essence of    
their profession. They decide which books, records, and videotapes will    
be made available to library patrons, and they routinely screen out    
materials that contradict their biases. Woe betide the independent-minded    
librarian who dares to defy them by respecting the values and opinions of    
the taxpayers who make their jobs possible. "The acceptance of moral    
responsibility for children in the library is now called 'unprofessional,"'    
notes Helen Chaffee Biehle; "making a responsible moral judgment about    
materials purchased for the library is called 'elitist,' and the librarian who    
is brave enough to do either is labeled a 'censor.'"   
 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




