<html>
<title>Average Household Faces $14,000 Tax Bill to Keep Medicare Afloat -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/pcpaper.jpg">
<center>
<img src="/heritage/pcr2.gif" width=445 height=78 alt="Physicians Council Report"><br>
<h3>AVERAGE HOUSEHOLD FACES $14,000 TAX BILL TO KEEP MEDICARE AFLOAT</h3>

<a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
Physicians Council Report No. 3<br>
June 20, 1996<br>
</center><hr width=50%>								
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	The tax bill for every household in America will come to $14,000 to keep Medicare afloat through the year 2005, according to a new Heritage Foundation analysis of the recent Medicare Trustees' report on the program's financial condition.


	<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As has been widely reported, the hospital insurance portion of Medicare (Part A) will run out of money in 2001, at which point it will literally be illegal for the program to pay full benefits.  To keep this segment of Medicare operating until 2005 will require a $400 billion bailout, or $4,000 in new taxes on every household in America, according to the Heritage analysis.
<p><i>
<a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/fyi110c1.gif">Chart 1:</a> Money Available to Pay Hospital Benefits<p>
</i>


	<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The situation for Medicare Part B, which covers doctor visits and other services, is in many ways even worse.  Under current law, the cost of Part B is paid partly by beneficiaries (about 30 percent) and partly by taxpayers (about 70 percent).  Yet, if no changes are made to Medicare, by 2005 the taxpayer share of Part B costs is projected to rise to 84 percent.  With Part B costs expected to total $1.2 trillion over the next 10 years, that translates into a taxpayer share of $950 billion, or $10,000 for every family in America.
<p><i>
<a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/fyi110c2.gif">Chart 2:</a> Who Pays for Part B Costs<p>
</i>
	<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite this bleak forecast, the Medicare Trustees balked at proposing serious solutions to the program's terminal financial condition.  Instead, they proposed a "national commission" to recommend solutions to Congress.  But all this will do is allow nervous politicians to believe they can avoid the issue of Medicare for a few more years, and by that point, the choices would be more limited and the necessary action more drastic.

	<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Congress and the White House should act now to repair Medicare's finances by making three structural changes to the program:<ol>

 <p><li>Turn Medicare into a "defined contribution" program, which would give seniors a specified amount of money to purchase health coverage instead of providing specific benefits.  
 
 <p><li>Allow Medicare recipients to choose from a wide range of health plans, which would give them access to fuller coverage (prescription drug benefits, for example) and spur competition between plans to hold down costs.  
 
<p><li>Reduce the Part B subsidy for those who don't need it, which would correct a costly situation in which millionaire seniors get just as much help paying their doctor bills as those who rely entirely on Social Security checks to make ends meet.

	</ol><p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Policy makers have limited choices when it comes to fixing Medicare: massive tax increases, draconian benefit cuts, or structural reforms.  Only the third choice makes any sense, and the quicker Congress and the White House begin those reforms, the less painful they will be.

<p><I>
NOTE: This brief Report is based on Heritage's F.Y.I. No. 110, <a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/fyi110.html">"Urgent Action Needed on Medicare"</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/butler.htm">Stuart M. Butler</a>, Vice President and Director of Domestic and Economic Policy Studies.  Heritage Foundation research and publications are available on the Internet through Heritage's homepage (<a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>).
<p>
<table border cellpadding=10>
<tr><td>
<center><b>WHAT YOU CAN DO</b></center><p>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
	There are many things physicians and patients can do to make their voices heard:<ul>

<p><li>Share your views about Medicare reform with your elected officials.  Call or write your 	Congressmen or Senators (To call, dial 202/224-3121 and ask for their office).  Or call 	the White House (202/456-1414).
 
<p><li>Go to the "town hall" meetings Members of Congress hold in their districts.  Let your 	representative know how you feel.
 
<p><li>Write letters to the editor of your local newspaper.  Voice your concerns on local radio 	programs.</ul><p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
	If you are a physician, share this Report with your patients and colleagues and encourage them to speak out.  If you are a patient, talk to your friends about Medicare reform, and tell your physician about the Physicians Council and this Report.  If you need more copies, contact The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Ave., N.E. Washington, D.C.  20002.  Phone:  202/546-4400, ext. 6050, or  e-mail: <a href="mailto: physicians@heritage.org">physicians@heritage.org</a>.</td></tr></table>
