<html>
<title>Cops and Doctors, Part II -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/pcpaper.jpg">
<center>
<img src="/heritage/pcr2.gif" width=445 height=78 alt="Physicians Council Report"><br>
<h3>COPS AND DOCTORS, PART II</H3>

by Grace-Marie Arnett<br>
<a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
Physicians Council Report No. 2<br>
May 1, 1996
</center><hr width=50%>                                                         
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
	The health care reform bills that have been approved by both the House and the Senate are being touted as a tiny step toward reform.  Perhaps, but when a giant like the federal government takes even a small step, it can create a thunderous reverberation.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

	Some of the provisions of the legislation may help -- like increasing the deductibility for health insurance for the self-employed to 80 percent by the year 2006.  Others are mixed: the requirement that individuals can purchase health insurance is designed to assure "portability," but state experiences indicate the new mandate likely will destabilize the market for private health insurance policies by driving up costs. 
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

	Still others are echoes of a health care reform bill that crashed to defeat less than two years ago.  The House bill and to a lesser extent the Senate bill contain a confusing plethora of new fines, penalties, and jail terms for doctors, with broadened investigative powers for federal agents.  These provisions are designed to stop the leakage of an estimated 10 percent of Medicare dollars that are lost to "waste, fraud and abuse," and to stop overcharges in private plans.  But experience proves that trying to enforce cost containment with laws rather than market dynamics is a no-win game.  In the process, a huge amount of expertise and expense goes toward compliance rather than patient care.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

	Here are some of the provisions drawn from the two bills that will be on the table when the House-Senate health care conferees go to work to produce a final bill:
<p><ul>
 <li>A new category of crime would be created, called "Federal Health Care Offenses."  Doctors could be sent to jail for 10 years if they misapply any assets used in health care, and they could be sentenced to life in prison if their wrongdoing results in a death.  They would go to jail for five years if they obstruct a health care investigation.
 <p>
 <li>A national health care Fraud and Abuse Control Program would be created to investigate the actions of doctors and other medical providers.  Doctors and health plans could be required to pay stiff civil penalties, forfeit property, and even pay for the investigations against them. In the House bill, the feds would issue special "Fraud Alerts" to warn people about offending doctors and health plans.
 <p>
 <li>Doctors could be fined up to $10,000 for delivering medically improper or unnecessary health care services, with the Secretary of Health and Human Services -- not patients and doctors -- defining what is medically necessary.
 <p>
 <li>A new crime is created for citizens who "knowingly and willfully" dispose of assets to qualify for Medicaid. They could be fined $25,000 or jailed for five years or both.
 <p>
 <li>Under the House bill, doctors also could be fined $5,000 or more if they certify that a patient who doesn't meet requirements is eligible for home health services.  
<p>
 <li>The federal government also would develop new standards for health plans to report financial and administrative information on patients.  The penalty for violating the standards:  up to $25,000 a year.  If the information is wrongfully disclosed: $250,000 and 10 years in jail.
<p>
 <li>The FBI would get involved in inspections, investigations, and prosecutions regarding health care matters with the aid of $47 million in additional funding next year and more each year after.  HHS also would get new money to go after doctors and health plans in the Medicare program -- more than $430 million in 1997, with funding increases each year.  The cost to taxpayers is only the tip of the iceberg; health care costs inevitably will rise as facilities devote even more resources to produce the information to defend themselves.
 <p>
 <li>The bills are very generous with long-term care services:  If a person needs help with any two daily living activities ("eating, toileting, transferring, bathing, dressing, or continence"), he or she would be eligible for payment under long-term care insurance -- which, by the way, receives a special new tax break.  Worse, any licensed health care provider, not just one associated with the insurer, could determine eligibility.
</ul><p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
 
	Certainly, if there are laws, they must be enforced.  But the requirements would be so confusing that doctors and patients would have trouble knowing the rules. Doctors, nurses, and health plans would be forced to focus even more on whether they are running afoul of a "Federal Health Care Offense" instead of treating their patients. If they slip up, they may find the FBI at their doorstep.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

	It is ironic that at a time when the Congress is trying to devolve more power to the states,  it is giving the federal government broad new powers to go after doctors, hospitals, and health plans -- powers that are eerily similar to those granted to the much-despised Internal Revenue Service.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

	A system based upon regulation requires tighter and tighter rules to close an ever-growing number of escape hatches.  Ultimately, regulators cannot win. The only way to stop this escalating spiral is to give individual consumers more control over decisions about their health coverage, not to further criminalize the health care system.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

	The bills do give patient watchdogs new incentives -- such as offering Medicare beneficiaries a payback for reporting erroneous billing.  The conferees are expected to go to work soon and hope to have a final bill on President Clinton's desk before Memorial Day. When they convene, they would be well advised to give cost-conscious consumers -- not a brigade of federal agents -- more control over health care dollars.

<p>				

Grace-Marie Arnett is vice president of The Heritage Foundation for Information Marketing Services.  She also serves as president of the Galen Institute, Inc., which studies market-based health care reform.  Elizabeth Kern assisted in the preparation of this report.
<p>
<table border cellpadding=10>
<tr><td>
<center><b>WHAT YOU CAN DO</b></center><p>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
There are many things physicians and patients can do to make their voices heard:
<p><ul>
<li> 	Share your views about health care reform with your elected officials.  Call or write your Congressmen or Senators (To call, dial 202/224-3121 and ask for their office).  Or call the White House (202/456-1414).
<p> 
<li>Go to the "town hall" meetings Members of Congress hold in their districts.  Let your representative know how you feel.
<p>
<li>Write letters to the editor of your local newspaper. Voice your concerns on local radio programs.
</ul>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;	If you are a physician, share this Report with your patients and colleagues and encourage them to speak out.  If you are a patient, talk to your friends about Medicare reform, and tell your physician about the Physicians Council and this Report.  If you need more copies, contact The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Ave., N.E. Washington, D.C.  20002.  Phone:  202/546-4400, ext. 6050, or  e-mail: <a href="mailto: physicians@heritage.org">physicians@heritage.org</a>.
</td></tr></table>
