<TITLE> Business/Education Insider #35 -- Heritage </TITLE>


<CENTER><H3> Business/Education Insider #35</H3>
Business/Education Insider<br>
January 1994  </CENTER>
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>

 

Features:  
 <P>
New California Superintendent 
<P>
Students Learn Less When Local Control Lost 
 <P>
RJR Nabisco Backs "Breaking China" 
 <P>
Project New Orleans Helps Poor 
 <P>
Good News for Michigan, Bad News on Adult Literacy 

<P>

PRIVATIZATION SAVES MONEY, REASON STUDY SHOWS  
<P>
     Business managers know that contracting out for certain goods and
services can save money and improve the quality of the final product. 
Unfortunately, most school administrators and local politicians have
yet to learn this lesson.  A recent guide published by the California-
based Reason Foundation, "Making Schools Work:  Contracting Options
for Better Management," finds that many schools pay as much as five
times what private companies pay for the same work in the same area. 
The foundation points out that school administrators can use
innovative management strategies, like contracting out, to stretch
available resources much further.
<P>
     Designed for public school administrators and managers, the guide
describes a wide variety of money-savving contracting options that
could improve both the educational quality and the physical plant of
public schools.  It will help officials decide when, what, and how to
contract with private organizations for services.  It also gives "how
to" guidelines for successful contracting. 
<P>
     According to Reason, most public school privatization occurs in
such areas as transportation, janitorial services, and food services. 
This is especially true for smaller school districts, where the cost
to taxpayers of keeping services "in house" -- which includes the
overhead costs of equipment, salaries, and insurance -- can be
disproportionately expensive.  Companies specializing in a specific
service generally operate on a larger scale and so can spread out
overhead costs, leading to lower prices.  Private contracting also
tends to eliminate the sloppiness and carelessness that often are
found in services operated by the public school system:  a private
company's contract can be terminated for poor performance.
<P>
     There are plenty of examples of successes in the Reason guide. 
In Piscataway, New Jersey, for example, School Superintendent Philip
Geiger privatized bus services in 1991 and cafeteria services in 1992. 
Within one year the transportation costs dropped from $4 million to
$2.5 million, while an estimated $500,000 was saved on food services
in one year.  With that $2 million in savings, says Geiger, "We were
able to redirect funds from noninstructional to instructional uses and
save tax dollars."  With such services delegated to private firms,
school administrators can focus more on what matters most:  educating
children.
<P>
     Privatization can also yield benefits for remedial education,
special education, driver's education, and foreign language
instruction.  Far fewer students enroll in these courses than in basic
courses such as Math and English, and hiring private companies to run
these classes can significantly reduce overall costs.  For example,
Berlitz International, the world-famous firm which offers foreign
language instruction to business executives and tourists, now serves
public schools.  High Tech High School, a magnet school in Hudson
County, New Jersey, contracts with Berlitz to teach Japanese and
Spanish.  Says Principal Karol Brantato, "It's economically feasible
for us....  [W]hat would we have done with a [full-time] Japanese
teacher on staff the rest of the time?  We're very happy with Berlitz,
and I think contracting out is a real viable option for small
programs."
<P>
     Because the needs and abilities of children are unique, some
children require additional assistance.  In Baltimore, Maryland, the
public school system signed a contract in 1993 with Sylvan Learning
Systems for remedial instruction to disadvantaged students in five
public schools.  If a student fails to improve his academic
performance, the company will offer an extra six weeks of remedial
education to the student at no charge to the schools. 
<P>
     One of the most innovative privatizing efforts is contracting out
the supervision of an entire school to a private company, a measure
used in some localities to halt the declining quality of public
education.  The leader in this field has been the Milwaukee-based
Education Alternatives, Inc.  (see BEI 8, 11, 18, 19, 21, 34).  In
June 1991, the firm signed a five-year contract with the Dade County,
Florida school district to operate one of their public schools.  The
company now also runs nine schools in Baltimore, where they in turn
have sub-contracted out to Johnson Controls World Services for
janitorial services.  Budgeted at the average per-pupil cost of the
school district , the company expects to cut administrative costs by
25 percent, redirect those funds into the classroom, and still make a
5 percent profit.  Preliminary results are promising.
<P>
     With growing budget demands,  school administrators are
desperately trying to find ways to cut costs yet still assure quality
education.  Contracting out services often costs less than providing
the service "in house."  It assures direct accountability, and would
be continued only if the school district found the relationship
successful.  Privatization, therefore, could prove to be a vital step
on the road to educational reform.
<P>
     To obtain a copy of the report, contact Janet Beales or John
O'Leary at the Reason Foundation, 3415 S.  Sepulveda Boulevard, Los
Angeles, CA 90034 or call (310) 391-2245.
<P>
     
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR NOMINATES BUSINESSMAN AS SUPERINTENDENT 
     <P>
     Governor Pete Wilson of California recently nominated corporate
turnaround specialist Sanford C.  Sigoloff for the post of
Superintendent of Public Instruction, the highest education position
in the state.  If confirmed, Sigoloff will take over from acting
Superintendent of Public Instruction William Dawson.
<P>
     Wilson hopes Sigoloff, Chairman and CEO of Sigoloff and
Associates, a Los Angeles-based consulting firm specializing in the
restructuring and rehabilitation of troubled companies, will apply the
same principles to education he has used in making corporate
California more competitive.  As Wilson says, "Now he [Sigoloff] has a
new customer -- the school children of California -- and these same
principles that helped make corporate America more competitive can be
put to work making our schools more competitive."
<P>
     Sigoloff, who is also an adjunct professor at the John E. 
Anderson Graduate School of Management at the University of
California-Los Angeles, will help school districts around the state
get the most out of taxpayers' dollars.  Declares Wilson, "We can't
afford to waste a single dollar on overhead or administration when we
need every dollar we have in the classroom helping our kids."
<P>
BIGGER DOES NOT EQUAL BETTER 
<P>
     The Chicago-based Heartland Institute warns that students
actually learn less when states, as opposed to local governments, pick
up a larger share of funding for public schools.
<P>
     Their report, "Losing Local Control of Education:  Cost and
Quality Implications," analyzed data for 37 states and the District of
Columbia, evaluating the relationship between student achievement and
school district size, school size, and state share of school funding. 
After controlling for per-pupil expenditures and the socio-economic
status of students, author Herbert J.  Walberg, who is Research
Professor of Education at the University of Illinois at Chicago, finds
that as school governance and funding become more centralized, student
achievement falls.  "The increasing bureaucracy and declining local
accountability that accompany 'remote' spending," writes Walberg,
"have a demonstrably negative effect on student achievement."
<P>
     Walberg shows that centralized funding, school district
consolidation, and a trend toward larger schools has reduced the
influence of parents, educators, and local school boards in
determining school policy.  It has, however, increased the influence
of special interest groups such as the National Education Association. 
The results of centralized governance and funding are all too clear: 
"School spending and school-related tax rates are more likely to
increase and to increase without accountability and improvement in
student learning.  States with such centralized systems are driven by
special interests rather than the public good, which in this case is
effective learning."
<P>
     For more information or a copy of the study, contact Diane Carol
Bast, publications director at the Heartland Institute, 634 S.  Wabash
Avenue, #200, Chicago, IL 60605, or call (708) 202-3060.
<P>
     
RJR NABISCO FOUNDATION BACKS RADICAL REFORM 
<P>
     The Next Century Schools Program, funded by the RJR Nabisco
Foundation, is attempting to stimulate education reform in America. 
After committing nearly $30 million to 42 schools with ideas for
school reform, the RJR Nabisco Foundation recently brought 75
principals, teachers, administrators, and others from across the
United States together for a three-day conference entitled the "China
Breakers Conference."
<P>
     The meeting, part of the Next Century Schools program, recognized
individuals committed to breaking the mold of schooling by channeling
their ideas and energies into the educational mainstream.  The
consensus:  Americans must break some china to enjoy the benefits of
schools that meet the needs of the changing society.  Said former
Chairman and CEO of RJR Nabisco, and now IBM CEO, Louis Gerstner: 
"The majority of our public schools are low-tech institutions in a
high-tech world -- bureaucratic dinosaurs lagging behind every
comparable system worldwide."
<P>
     The participants agreed radical reform must take place if America
is going to be competitive in the world economy during the next
century.  Among the recommendations of the conference:  entitle
parents, students, and teachers to greater choice among and within
schools, decentralize school administration, abolish certification,
and establish high, uniform, and demanding standards for students and
teachers.
<P>
     Conferees agreed that real school choice was the most important
ingredient in school reform.  Notes From the Front Lines, the
published highlights of the conference, concludes:  "School choice... 
was the natural, inevitable consequence of the new concept the
participants were struggling to create, a paradigm emphasizing
community, 'smallness' as an educational value and new learning
experiences created by cottage industries.  Greater choice can
stimulate the energy and creativity of parents, students and teachers
that are smothered in today's bureaucratic schools." 
<P>
     Another forthcoming development of the Next Century Schools
project is the forthcoming book, Reinventing Education.  Authored by
IBM chief Gerstner, New American Schools Development Corporation
treasurer Roger Semerad, education analyst Denis Doyle, and William
Johnston, it will emphasize the need for radical reform of America's
education system.  The book warns that "schools cannot be regulated
back into good health," and that only a business (or market-based)
perspective of reforming American public schools will work. 
<P>
     Reinventing Education gives many examples of innovative ideas
used by schools in the Next Century Schools project.  The Downtown
School in Winston-Salem, North Carolina, for instance, is an example
of what a school can accomplish when unencumbered by existing notions
of schools.  The Downtown School is located in a former public market,
near a corporate complex.  The children of nearby workers are given
enrollment priority.  These workers must agree to help out at the
school at least one hour per week as a condition of enrolling their
children.  As an increasing number of parents work outside the home,
the close ties between schools and workplace become more important.
<P>
     The Next Century Schools project is at the forefront of reforming
the American education system.  Only by breaking through the current
mindset that accepts the status quo will American business make a real
difference in education.
<P>
     For more information, write the RJR Nabisco Foundation, Suite
525, 1455 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Washington, DC 20004, or phone
(202)626-7200.  <P>
BUSINESSMAN GIVES EDUCATIONAL OPPORTUNITY TO POOR CHILDREN 
<P>
     Patrick F.  Taylor, owner of Taylor Energy Company of New
Orleans, is among the growing band of business leaders who are giving
educational opportunities to low-income youngsters.
<P>
     Taylor's commitment to the education of poor youngsters began in
1988 after he addressed 180 twice-failed, minority, single-parent
seventh- and eighth-grade students at Livingston Middle School in East
New Orleans.  At the time, many of these students planned to drop out
of school after the eighth grade.  But by serving as a role model and
encouraging these children, Taylor has helped many of them enter
college.
<P>
     One of Taylor's major efforts, Project New Orleans, gives $1,000
in personal expense money per year to each student in Orleans Parish
who qualifies for a Pell Grant and is enrolled in a Louisiana college. 
The program, which has been in effect since 1990, helps students with
necessary funds for transportation, books, clothing, lab fees, and
other classroom materials or incidental expenses.
<P>
     According to Taylor, Project New Orleans is aimed at inner-city
children because of their high dropout rates, ranging from 45 percent
to 60 percent, and because, he says, many have no hope of a future
"beyond crime, poverty or welfare."  The extra help is critical: 
"While a waiver of tuition and fees would assist them in college, many
do not have additional finances to buy books, pay for transportation
or other incidentals necessary during their college career."  Taylor
has thus far convinced eighteen New Orleans companies to invest over
$2 million in this program.
<P>
     For more on Project New Orleans, contact the Taylor Energy
Company, 234 Loyola Avenue, Suite 500, New Orleans, LA 70112, (504)
581-5491.<P>
MICHIGAN ENACTS CHARTER SCHOOL LEGISLATION 
<P>
     Governor John Engler and the Michigan legislature recently took a
step toward reforming Michigan's troubled education system.  Following
the landmark legislative decision last year to eliminate all state
property taxes earmarked for schools (see BEI #33), Engler and his
allies in the state legislature worked successfully to pass some of
his educational reform agenda.  The centerpiece is charter school
legislation, which enables existing public schools, community
colleges, and universities to set up schools.  Michigan is the eighth
state to establish charter schools.  The others are California,
Colorado, Georgia, Minnesota, New Mexico, Massachusetts, and
Wisconsin. 
<P>
     Under the legislation, no limitation is set on who may propose to
create an "academy," or charter school, but only existing public
schools, community colleges, or public universities are authorized to
organize and operate one or more public academies.   To ensure
accountability, charter schools must take the MEAP (Michigan Education
Assessment Program) test or any national assessment test.  The
Governor's allies won a major battle against Outcome-Based Education
proponents by inserting a provision that the MEAP test could not test
for values.  In addition, there is no teacher tenure in an "academy"
school, and in a related bill, the legislature made it easier for
qualified people without a teaching degree to become certified through
an accelerated program.
<P>
     Citizen groups in Michigan are also trying to eliminate the
state's constitutional ban against private school choice.  Clearly,
Michigan's education reform has just begun.
<P>
     For more information, contact Bob Wittmann at the Mackinac Center
for Public Policy, 119 Ashman Street, P.O.  Box 568, Midland, MI
48640, or call (517) 631-0900.

     <P>

     
ALL ADULTS LACK BASIC WORK SKILLS 
<P>
     A recent study by the Department of Education presents a bleak
picture of the nation's literacy.  According to the four-year study,
nearly half of America's 191 million adult citizens cannot write a
coherent letter about a billing error or calculate the length of a bus
trip from a bus schedule.
<P>
     Like other studies on literacy, the new government report says
that about 10 percent of all adult Americans admit they have
difficulty reading and writing.  But this study gives a more detailed
picture of America's literacy problem than previous reports have done,
since it takes into account how well people understand English.  The
study also includes questions requiring competence in addition and
subtraction.
<P>
     The price of illiteracy is borne chiefly by businesses and their
employees.  Business leaders estimate a $25 billion to $30 billion
loss per year in productivity because of errors attributable to poor
literacy.  Needless to say, the business community was not surprised
about the results of the recent study.  Said Brenda Bell, vice
president of marketing for the National Alliance of Business, "We have
estimated that only about 25 percent of the adult population is highly
literate."
<P>
     A growing number of companies are trying to address illiteracy
through worker training programs.  Many form partnerships with local
community colleges, where professors come to offices and factories to
help workers learn basic skills.
<P>
     But while businesses are pouring billions of dollars into
workforce training and education programs, they still have very little
to show for their efforts.  Madeleine M.  Kunin, Deputy Secretary of
Education, worries that "We simply are not keeping pace with the kinds
of skills required in today's economy."  More and more business
leaders are concluding that trying to solve the literacy problem at
the workplace is starting too late, and that the education system
needs genuine systemic change.
<P>
     For a copy of this report, write Education Information Branch,
OERI, U.S.  Department of Education, 555 New Jersey Avenue, N.W.,
Washington, DC 20208-5641, or call (800) 424-1616.

<P>
SPEAKER'S CORNER 
 <P>
Despite rhetoric to the contrary, a lack of money has not been
responsible for the decline in educational achievement for the last
ten years.  Consider the facts:  
<P>
      
Total spending by all levels of government on education in 1993 was
$493.3 billion.  
<P>
Total spending on education, after adjusting for inflation, has risen
over 50 percent since 1983.  
<P>
      
The proportion of the United States' gross domestic product spent on
education rose from 6.7 percent in 1983 to 7.9 percent in 1993.  
<P>
Source:  The United States Department of Education.  
<P>
