<HTML>
<TITLE>Business/Education Insider -- Heritage </TITLE>

<CENTER><H3> No.  37</H3>
Business/Education Insider
June/July 1994 
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>

Features:  
<P>
Choice:  A State-By-State Breakdown 
<P>
Louisiana Business Leaders Seek to Reform Education "Fiefdoms" 
      <P>
Enterprise New Zealand Teaches Business Skills 
<P>
Nearly 5,000 Needy Students Helped By Private Vouchers 
      
<P>
SCHOOL CHOICE CONTINUES TO GAIN GROUND 
 <P>   Business leaders and others supporting true education reform can
take heart from the surge of school choice legislation over the past
year.  Whether confined to public schools or expanded to include
private and parochial schools, school choice bills are moving in state
after state.  In fact, choice is the centerpiece of a growing grass
roots challenge to a government-run school system that is failing in
many areas of the country, particularly in America's inner cities.
 <P>   A clear pattern is emerging, according to the annual survey of
school choice measures published recently by The Heritage Foundation.
In 1993, some form of school choice legislation was introduced or
pending in 34 states.  In addition, 33 state governors have indicated
support for some form of school choice, up from 29 in 1992.  And, most
important, at least 35 states have parents' and grassroots' coalitions
working for school choice reforms.  Thus, despite the defeat last
November of Proposition 174, a major school choice initiative in
California (see BEI # 34), and the recent narrow defeat of a school
choice bill in the Arizona legislature, the movement continues to grow
stronger.
<P>     Voucher Programs a Success. Voucher programs passed in earlier
years continued successfully in 1993.  For example, the Wisconsin
state legislature in 1989 introduced a voucher program for Milwaukee
(see BEI # 3).  Currently, 1,000 low-income children can obtain a
voucher worth as much as $2,967 to attend a private school.  Despite
the bitter opposition of education bureaucrats, including the state
school boards association and the teachers unions, the Milwaukee
choice program withstood legal challenges and is forcing changes in
Wisconsin's educational establishment.  
  <P>   Although religious schools have space available in Milwaukee,
only 742 students received vouchers during the 1993-1994 school year
because religious schools are barred from the program and there is not
enough space available in other private schools. To use this space
availability more effectively, Milwaukee Mayor John Norquist and
Wisconsin State Representative Polly Williams have called on state
legislators to increase the number of eligible students  from 1,000 to
5,000. This would be done by letting the students attend not just
secular private schools, but also parochial schools.
  <P>  In addition, the Landmark Legal Foundation, a public interest law
firm, has filed a lawsuit to expand the Milwaukee program. The suit,
on behalf of low-income families in Wisconsin, asks a federal court in
Milwaukee to include parochial schools in the Milwaukee Parental
Choice Program.  Landmark's attorneys claim prohibiting the use of the
vouchers at religious schools is a violation of the plaintiffs'
constitutional right to the free exercise of religion and equal
protection under the law.  
 <P>    The past year also saw the most comprehensive school choice law
yet passed in the United States.  Puerto Rico's Governor Pedro Rosello
signed into law an educational voucher system for the entire territory
of Puerto Rico (see BEI #33). The vouchers, limited to $1,500 each,
offer families the opportunity to choose the public or private school
for their child. The new law also gives high school students the
opportunity to take university-level courses.  While opponents have
challenged the Puerto Rico reform in the courts, school choice
advocates are confident they will prevail.
   <P>  Open enrollment legislation, which gives parents the right to
choose the public school their child will attend, also has been making
headway.  Currently, six states offer "intradistrict open enrollment,"
meaning parents can choose a school within the confines of their
child's school district. Ten states have enacted "interdistrict open
enrollment plans," meaning parents can choose any public school within
the state, not just within their local district.  In addition, seven
states now have voluntary intradistrict plans, and four states have
voluntary interdistrict plans under which school districts can choose
to offer the programs.  And finally, six states have special,
district-based intradistrict plans in which individual cities have
implemented choice programs. 
  <P>  Charter Schools Explosion. Legislation creating chartered,
autonomous public schools is gaining ground, too.  Charter schools are
schools run by teachers, parents, principals, and others outside the
education bureaucracy, and are subject to much less regulation.  Prior
to 1993, two states had enacted charter school legislation: California
and Minnesota.
  <P>   In 1993, thirteen state legislatures considered charter school
legislation or the expansion of existing charter school laws.  Of
these, six states enacted such legislation: Colorado, Georgia,
Massachusetts, Michigan, New Mexico, and Wisconsin.  In early 1994,
Kansas became the ninth state to pass charter school legislation.
Private Voucher Programs Flourish. While legislative reformers were
busy introducing school choice initiatives, many business leaders took
matters into their own hands through private voucher programs. These
privately funded programs are designed to help low-income families
afford the school of their choice for their children.  During the
1993-1994 school year, over 5,000 low-income students have been able
to attend private schools as a result of these efforts.
  <P>   Private scholarship programs were pioneered by businessman Peter
Flanigan of Dillon, Read, & Company (See BEI #6, 9, 30, 34) in 1986.
His "Student-Sponsor Partnership" enabled 725 low-income high school
students in New York to attend private schools in the 1993-94 school
year.
   <P>  Likewise, the Golden Rule Insurance Company's Indianapolis-based
"CHOICE Charitable Trust" scholarship program has been an inspiration
to many corporate and philanthropic charities. Working with other
business groups in Indiana, the Trust helps poor children in
Indianapolis attend private schools  by awarding scholarships covering
up to half their tuition costs. During the 1993-1994 school year, some
1,100 pupils used these vouchers. While the education establishment
has vigorously attacked Golden Rule CEO J. Patrick Rooney, business
and philanthropic organizations see the benefits of the program and
are emulating it.  In 1993, there were eleven private scholarship
programs based on the Golden Rule model, up from five in 1992.  In
addition, at least three other cities are planning to begin similar
programs in September 1994.
  <P>   Public Supports Choice. The growth of school choice initiatives
coincides with strong public support for school choice.  For instance,
in a January 1994 telephone poll of Minnesotans conducted by the
Gordon S. Black Corporation for the Center of the American Experiment
in Minneapolis, Minnesota, some 61% of the respondents favored
introduction of a voucher system.  In addition, 86% of the respondents
supported the interdistrict, public school choice program currently in
place in Minnesota.<P>
For a copy of the 1994 edition of The Heritage Foundation's School
Choice Programs: What's Happening in the States, write the
Publications Department, Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002, or call the Publications
Department at (202) 546-4400.
<P>
LOUISIANA BUSINESS GROUP STRESSES NEED FOR RADICAL REFORM 
 <P>    After a decade of failed reform in the Louisiana school system,
Louisiana business leaders are now calling for radical reform.
According to "Getting There . . . A Better Tomorrow Beginning Today,"
a recent report of the Louisiana Association of Business & Industry,
"Piecemeal attempts to change the present system in Louisiana haven't
worked and won't work.  The present system is a monopoly, and it has
no incentive to change."
<P>     Like other states, Louisiana has poured billions of dollars into
its public elementary and secondary schools. The state spent
approximately 60 percent of its revenues (excluding federal funds) 
$2.4 billion  on education in 1991-1992, the latest year for which
figures are available. In addition, the state spent $5.2 million in
1991-1992 on remediation in the elementary and secondary schools, and
another $14 million is spent on remediation in the state's colleges
and universities.
<P>     Despite this level of spending, Louisiana ranked 40th among the
41 states which gave their eighth graders the National Assessment of
Educational Progress (NAEP) math test in 1992.  In addition, a recent
U.S. Department of Education report says  about 58 percent of fourth
graders in the state read below the "basic" level and cannot
understand simple stories.
 <P>    Along with pouring more money into their schools, Louisiana has
lowered its class sizes over the past twenty years.  Between the
1971-1972 and 1991-1992 school years, the number of students in public
schools dropped 12 percent.  Despite this drop in enrollment, the
number of school employees went up 27 percent. Yet, the report states,
"Education in Louisiana is run like a collection of warring fiefdoms 
each protecting its own turf and seeking more money and power  after
losing sight of the goal: the education of the people."
  <P>   In order to overcome the inertia of the present bureaucratic
system, the Louisiana Association of Business and Industry recommends
establishing public charter schools and a voucher program which would
allow parents to choose among government and nongovernmental schools. 
<P>
For a copy of the report, contact the Louisiana Association of
Business and Industry, 3113 Valley Creek Drive, P. O. Box 80258, Baton
Rouge, LA 70898-0258, or call (504) 928-5388.

<P>
NEW ZEALAND BUSINESS GROUP EDUCATES STUDENTS AND TEACHERS IN BUSINESS
PRINCIPLES 
  <P>   Business leaders' frustration with the lack of general business
knowledge among students is not confined to America. A private group
of business leaders in New Zealand have formed Enterprise New Zealand
Trust.  Its goal: a nationwide program to promote business and
economic education in the schools. According to Ken Baker, Executive
Director of Enterprise New Zealand, "It is now realized that if we are
to improve the standard of living of future New Zealanders, then we
need to be much more enterprising, [and] that we need to develop a
positive attitude towards business . . . . In our schools, we had a
non business culture. School programs operate as though business were
an aberration.  Given their background this is not surprising."
<P>     One of the trust's programs, Enterprise Studies, teaches
entrepreneurial skills to students through contact with local
enterprises, including businesses and volunteer agencies, both as
sources of information and as subjects of study.  After studying
entrepreneurship in the classroom, students are given the chance to
use their new skills by running some form of short-term enterprise.
  <P>   Enterprise New Zealand also instructs teachers and principals in
the principles of entrepreneurship and economics.  These instructional
courses have been extremely helpful in enabling teachers and
principals to apply the techniques of business in the classroom.  One
graduate, Barry Bean, the Principal of Mount Maunganui College,
comments: "I firmly believe that many of the procedures/ methods of
the business world can be transferred to schools.  I am more than
happy to promote the merits of the Principles of Management course to
our local group of Principals."  
<P>
For more information, contact Enterprise New Zealand Trust, 2nd Floor,
BP House, 20 Customhouse Quay, P. O. Box 892, Wellington, or call
64-4-495 5926. Fax: 64-4-495 5924.
<P>

PRIVATE VOUCHER UPDATE 
 <P>    A recent report from The National Scholarship Center, Just Doing
It: First Annual Survey of the Private Voucher Movement in America,
shows the private voucher movement is picking up momentum all over the
country. According to the report, nearly 5,000 needy elementary and
secondary students are benefitting from one of eleven established
private voucher programs based on the model first developed by the
Golden Rule Insurance Company.  The survey addresses topics ranging
from the number and kinds of schools involved, to the income and other
characteristics of the children and families served, to the
administrative rules and operation of the programs. It gives a
prognosis for the future and lists programs that are likely to be
launched in the 1994-1995 school year.
 <P>    The comprehensive survey is only one of many indications that the
private voucher movement is beginning to receive the attention it
deserves. For instance, Golden Rule, which launched the Educational
CHOICE Charitable Trust program in Indianapolis, Indiana, was among
the 101 companies nationwide selected by members of the United States
Senate and Childhelp USA, a private organization working to combat
child abuse and neglect, to receive special recognition for unique
programs that are helping children and their families to succeed.     
Educational CHOICE Charitable Trust's executive director, Timothy P.
Ehrgott, accepted Golden Rule's award at a Congressional Awards
Luncheon hosted by Senator Orrin Hatch and Congressman Charles Rangel. 
Commented Ehrgott, "We only wish that the CHOICE families could be
with us in Washington.  They are the ones who have made enormous
sacrifices and deserve all the recognition.  We are just pleased to
have been able to help."
  <P>  The private voucher movement has hit even the nation's capital. 
Beginning in the Spring 1994 semester, scholarships became available
for grades K-8 to students who live in the District of Columbia and
are eligible for federally funded (free or reduced-price) school
lunches.  The scholarships are offered by the Washington Scholarship
Fund on a first-come, first-served basis and cover half of private
school tuition, up to a maximum of $1,500.  This semester, 50
scholarships were made available.  
<P>     Contributors to the Washington Scholarship Fund include such
major donors as Applied Energy Systems, the Bradley Foundation, and
business leaders such as Roger Naill, Robert J. Thompson, Randall
Byrnes, Patrick Rooney, and Earle Williams, in addition to a number of
smaller individual donors, including The Heritage Foundation. 
For a copy of  Just Doing It, contact the National Scholarship Center,
One Massachusetts Avenue, N.W., Suite 330, Washington, DC 20001, or
call (202) 842-1355. 
<P>
SPEAKER'S CORNER
<P>
      In a recent poll, voters in New Jersey were asked, "Do you
approve or disapprove of allowing Jersey City to test a pilot school
choice program where parents would receive publicly-funded vouchers so
that they could send their children to the public, private, or
parochial, school of their choice.
<P>
